mainmatter.p:
The exponentials of sheaves coincide with those of presheaves. To see this, we assume X^Y is the exponential of sheaves and calculate
\begin {aligned}      \Gamma (U, X^Y)     &=  \hom _{ \mathsf { Psh } }( \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U), X^Y)  \\      &=  \hom _{ \mathsf { Sh } }( \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U)^{++}, X^Y)  \\      &=  \hom _{ \mathsf { Sh } }(Y  \times   \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U)^{++}, X)  \\      &=  \hom _{ \mathsf { Sh } }(Y^{++}  \times   \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U)^{++}, X)  \\      &=  \hom _{ \mathsf { Sh } }((Y  \times   \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U))^{++}, X)  \\      &=  \hom _{ \mathsf { Psh } }(Y  \times   \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U), X)  \\     \end {aligned}
which is evidently \Gamma (U, X^Y) but this time the exponential is taken in the category of presheaves. We used the fact that the plus construction preserves finite product. However, we still need to prove that this indeed forms a sheaf.

Now we just need to pick out the class of morphisms S  \hookrightarrow   \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U) using the Lawvere–Tierney operator j. Note that this operator does not necessarily live in a presheaf topos, so we must find a way to generalize this class of arrows to not necessarily representable presheaves. Since every presheaf is a colimit of representables, we can look at the corresponding colimit of morphisms \operatorname *{colim}  S_i  \hookrightarrow   \operatorname *{colim}   \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U_i). A local object will satisfy
\begin {aligned}      \hom ( \operatorname *{colim} \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U_i), X)  \cong   \lim \hom ( \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U_i), X)  \quad   \\       \xrightarrow { \sim }  \lim \hom (S_i, X)  \cong   \hom ( \operatorname *{colim}  S_i, X).    \end {aligned}
Hence we can safely include these arrows into the class and still get the same concept of local objects. Now it's illuminating to look at the characteristic maps. A sieve S  \to   \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U) corresponds to a characteristic map in \hom ( \mathop { \mkern {-2mu} \text {よ} \mkern {-2mu}} (U),  \Omega )  \cong   \Gamma (U,  \Omega ). Generalizing to an arbitrary presheaf expressed (canonically) as a colimit of representables, we need the image of every section to be a covering sieve.
